#: index.docbook:103
msgid "How Interfaces Work"
msgstr "Comment fonctionne l'interface"

#: index.docbook:107
msgid ""
"&MCOP; interfaces are the base of the &arts; concept. They are the network "
"transparent equivalent to C++ classes. Whenever possible you should orient "
"your design towards interfaces. Interfaces consist of four parts:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:114
msgid "Synchronous streams"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:114
msgid "Asynchronous streams"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:114
msgid "Methods"
msgstr "Méthodes"

#: index.docbook:114
msgid "Attributes"
msgstr "Attributs"

#: index.docbook:121
msgid ""
"These can be mixed in any way you like. New technologies should be defined "
"in terms of interfaces. Read the sections about asynchronous streams and "
"synchronous streams, as well as the KMedia2 interfaces, which are a good "
"example how such things work"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:128
msgid ""
"Interfaces are specified in <literal role=\"extension\">.idl</literal> code "
"and run through the <command>mcopidl</command> compiler. You derive the "
"<classname><replaceable>Interfacename</replaceable>_impl</classname> class "
"to implement them, and use "
"<function>REGISTER_IMPLEMENTATION(Interfacename_impl)</function> to insert "
"your object implementations into the &MCOP; object system."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:141
msgid "Codecs - Data Decoding"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:143
msgid ""
"The kmedia2 interfaces allow you to ignore that wav files, mp3s and whatever "
"consist of data streams. Instead, you only implement methods to play them."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:149
msgid ""
"Thus, you can write a wave loading routine in a way that you can play wave "
"files (as PlayObject), but nobody else can use your code."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:154
msgid ""
"Asynchronous streams would be the alternative. You define an interface which "
"allows you to pass data blocks in, and get data blocks out. This looks like "
"that in &MCOP;:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:160
msgid ""
"interface Codec {\n"
"  in async byte stream indata;\n"
"  out async byte stream outdata;\n"
"};"
msgstr ""
"interface Codec {\n"
"  in async byte stream indata;\n"
"  out async byte stream outdata;\n"
"};"

#: index.docbook:168
msgid ""
"Of course codecs could also provide attributes to emit additional data, such "
"as format information."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:173
msgid ""
"interface ByteAudioCodec {\n"
"  in async byte stream indata;\n"
"  out async byte stream outdata;\n"
"  readonly attribute samplingRate, bits, channels;\n"
"};"
msgstr ""
"interface ByteAudioCodec {\n"
"  in async byte stream indata;\n"
"  out async byte stream outdata;\n"
"  readonly attribute samplingRate, bits, channels;\n"
"};"

#: index.docbook:181
msgid ""
"This <interfacename>ByteAudioCodec</interfacename> for instance could be "
"connected to a <interfacename>ByteStreamToAudio</interfacename> object, to "
"make real float audio."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:187
msgid ""
"Of course, other Codec types could involve directly emitting video data, "
"such as"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:192
msgid ""
"interface VideoCodec {\n"
"  in async byte stream indata;\n"
"  out video stream outdata;      /* note: video streams do not exist yet */\n"
"};"
msgstr ""
"interface VideoCodec {\n"
"  in async byte stream indata;\n"
"  out video stream outdata;      /* note: video streams do not exist yet */\n"
"};"

#: index.docbook:199
msgid ""
"Most likely, a codec concept should be employed rather than the <quote>you "
"know how to play and I don't</quote> way for instance "
"<interfacename>WavPlayObject</interfacename> currently uses. However, "
"somebody needs to sit down and do some experiments before an "
"<acronym>API</acronym> can be finalized."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:210
msgid "Video"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:212
msgid ""
"My idea is to provide video as asynchronous streams of some native &MCOP; "
"data type which contains images. This data type is to be created yet. Doing "
"so, plugins which deal with video images could be connected the same way "
"audio plugins can be connected."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:219
msgid "There are a few things that are important not to leave out, namely:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:223
msgid "There are <acronym>RGB</acronym> and <acronym>YUV</acronym> colorspaces."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:223
msgid "The format should be somehow tagged to the stream."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:223
msgid "Synchronization is important."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:241
msgid ""
"My idea is to leave it possible to reimplement the "
"<classname>VideoFrame</classname> class so that it can store stuff in a "
"shared memory segment. Doing so, even video streaming between different "
"processes would be possible without too much pain."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:248
msgid ""
"However, the standard situation for video is that things are in the same "
"process, from the decoding to the rendering."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:253
msgid ""
"I have done a prototypic video streaming implementation, which you can "
"download <ulink "
"url=\"http://space.twc.de/~stefan/kde/download/video-quickdraw.tar.gz\">"
"here </ulink>. This would need to be integrated into &MCOP; after some "
"experiments."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:261
msgid ""
"A rendering component should be provided that supports XMITSHM (with "
"<acronym>RGB</acronym> and <acronym>YUV</acronym>), Martin Vogt told me he "
"is working on such a thing."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:270
msgid "Threading"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:272
msgid ""
"Currently, &MCOP; is all single threaded. Maybe for video we will no longer "
"be able to get around threading. Ok. There are a few things that should be "
"treated carefully:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:279
msgid ""
"SmartWrappers - they are not threadsafe due to non-safe reference counting "
"and similar."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:279
msgid "Dispatcher / I/O - also not threadsafe."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:292
msgid ""
"However, what I could imagine is to make selected modules threadsafe, for "
"both, synchronous and asynchronous streaming. That way - with a thread aware "
"flow system, you could schedule the signal flow over two or more processors. "
"This would also help audio a lot on multiprocessor things."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:300
msgid "How it would work:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:305
msgid "The Flow System decides which modules should calculate what - that is:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:305
msgid "video frames (with process_indata method)"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:305
msgid "synchronous audio streams (calculateBlock)"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:305
msgid "other asynchronous streams, mainly byte streams"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:305
msgid ""
"Modules can calculate these things in own threads. For audio, it makes sense "
"to reuse threads (&eg; render on four threads for four processors, no matter "
"if 100 modules are running). For video and byte decompression, it may be "
"more confortable to have a blocking implementation in an own thread, which "
"is synchronized against the rest of &MCOP; by the flow system."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:305
msgid ""
"Modules may not use &MCOP; functionality (such as remote invocations) during "
"threaded operation."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:340
msgid "Synchronization"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:342
msgid ""
"Video and &MIDI; (and audio) may require synchonization. Basically, that is "
"timestamping. The idea I have is to attach timestamps to asynchronous "
"streams, by adding one timestamp to each packet. If you send two video "
"frames, simply make it two packets (they are large anyway), so that you can "
"have two different time stamps."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:350
msgid "Audio should implicitely have time stamps, as it is synchronous."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:357
msgid "Dynamic Composition"
msgstr ""

